76561198007789156,Recommended,220160,29728707,Posted: 5 February,all,Yamadog32,"If you are a person with excellent eye hand/finger coordination then this game is for you. If you like platformer puzzles and you have said eye hand skills then this game is for you. If you are just average or a little less skilled like me then you will have fun up to a point and then hit the wall with this game.Real world Trials is nothing like this game. I doubt anybody know what ""trials"" is as a motorsport. That does not matter for this game. You have a bike and you need to complete courses within a time limit to get medals to advance through the game. Medals get you new tracks and bikes. You earn money but it has no point other than you can buy parts to make your bike look different. They do nothing for performance so you can ignore them if you want.The game is fun. You get big air on some jumps. You can do back/forward flips all you want. It does nothing for your score but its fun and thats the point. There are some odd challenges like skiing on dirt, or trying to do a course with the throttle stuck wide open on your bike.The game rewards your own gifted skills if your are skilled. You have complete control of your bike and rider and far as brakes and throttle. You dont turn in this game so cornering is out. Your rider has a huge effect on the bike balance. The rider can lift the front or rear wheels off the ground just by leaning forward or backwards. This is how you conquer the the challenges. This is my most serious complaint about the handling of the game. You control the rider with the left stick on your game pad. It is super sensitive. I wish I could slow that down like mouse sensitivity in other games. So when you move him up or back he yanks the bike a bunch. Like I said I am not in the top 10% of skilled people.The game is fun. You crash a lot but you will make unbelievable saves that make you shout out loud. I got it cheap and played it a lot over the holidays but when I fired it up later on I just got frustrated."
